TY  - JOUR
T1  - Cultural Variations in the Cross-Border Transfer of Organizational Knowledge: An Integrative Framework
AU  - Bhagat, Rabi S.
AU  - Kedia, Ben L.
AU  - Harveston, Paula D.
AU  - Triandis, Harry C.
Y1  - 2002/04/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2002.6588000
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2002.6588000
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 204
EP  - 221
VL  - 27
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Little is known about the effectiveness of cross-border transfer of organizational knowledge involving dissimilar cultural contexts. We propose a theoretical framework for understanding the significance of four transacting cultural patterns, defined in terms of the dimensions of individualism-collectivism and verticalness-horizontalness, for their potential in moderating the effectiveness of cross-border transfer of organizational knowledge. Drawing foundational support for this new framework from recent research advances in the area of knowledge transfer, we explore implications for future research.
AB  - Little is known about the effectiveness of cross-border transfer of organizational knowledge involving dissimilar cultural contexts. We propose a theoretical framework for understanding the significance of four transacting cultural patterns, defined in terms of the dimensions of individualism-collectivism and verticalness-horizontalness, for their potential in moderating the effectiveness of cross-border transfer of organizational knowledge. Drawing foundational support for this new framework from recent research advances in the area of knowledge transfer, we explore implications for future research.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2002.6588000
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2002.6588000
Y2  - 2026/04/24
